ilosophy as something separate from the sciences and the humanities but also intimately connected to their processes, and he explicates a conception of truth that emphasizes fidelity and participation through dialogue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Deconstruction.2bisacsh1 aD'Agostini, Franca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aD’Agostini, Franca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCuaig, William.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/vatt1524240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231527125423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231527125/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK